## What happened

**`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS in .NET 11.** Apple's Security.framework never natively supported DSA. Earlier .NET versions shimmed it via OpenSSL, but Microsoft has been deprecating DSA (warning [`SYSLIB0028`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/fundamentals/syslib-diagnostics/syslib0028)) for several releases and .NET 11 drops macOS support entirely.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), you have two practical options:

### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended, cross-platform)

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] publicKeyDer, byte[] data, byte[] signature)
{
    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyDer);
    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

### Option 2 — Guard with a runtime check

If DSA still works on your Linux/Windows targets:

```csharp
public static bool VerifyLegacyDsa(byte[] data, byte[] signature, byte[] publicKey)
{
    if (!OperatingSystem.IsLinux() && !OperatingSystem.IsWindows())
        throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification requires Linux or Windows.");

    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    dsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKey, out _);
    return dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
}
```

**Recommendation:** Go with **BouncyCastle**. It gives you consistent behavior on all three platforms and avoids chasing future deprecations in the BCL.
